\f0\b\fs56 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0 Unix File System (UFS) \f1\b0\fs52 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0 \ \'a5 implements the on-disk format used by BSD, Solaris, and many other\ Unix-like operating systems\ \'a5 LFS modularity and change descriptors help simplify UFS code\

\f0\b\fs56 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0 Changegroup\cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0 Case Study \f1\b0\fs52 \ \'a5 To assess the utility of changegroups in a real world application, we updated\ the University of Washington's IMAP mail server to take advantage of\ changegroups\ \'a5 Each IMAP command is performed within a changegroup and is made\ dependent on the preceding command\ \'a5 Mailbox checkpoints sync the current changegroup to disk\ \'a5 Benefits:\ \'a5 Correctness is easier (changegroups capture all changes implicitly)\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0 \ \'a5 Fewer syncs are needed for correctness (e.g. message copies), resulting in\ fewer writes to disk}

{\rtf1\mac\ansicpg10000\cocoartf824\cocoasubrtf330 {\fonttbl\f0\fswiss\fcharset77 Helvetica;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural
\f0\fs52 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0 A complete Kudos configuration is composed of many modules with three major interfaces:\ \ \'a5 Virtual File System (VFS)\ \'a5 Abstract file and folder operations (e.g. open/write files)\ \'a5 Block Devices (BD)\ \'a5 Abstract disk block operations (e.g. read/write blocks)\ \'a5 Low-level File System (LFS)\ \'a5 Abstract file system structure operations (e.g. allocate a\ block, append a block to a file)\ \ The novel LFS interface separates high- and low-level file system operations, simplifying development of high-level modules (reading a file) and low-level modules (locating a block). High-level modules arrange change descriptors to preserve Unix consistency semantics across multiple LFS operations.\ \ All modules in the system can create, inspect, and modify change descriptors, allowing them to specify or adjust disk write ordering requirements. Modules need not understand each other's consistency protocols.}

{\rtf1\mac\ansicpg10000\cocoartf824\cocoasubrtf330 {\fonttbl\f0\fswiss\fcharset77 Helvetica;\f1\fswiss\fcharset77 Helvetica-Bold;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural
\f0\fs52 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0 \'a5 File systems order disk writes so that in the event of a crash, data is recoverable\ (e.g. \'d2Soft Updates\'d3 in UFS)\ \'a5 For example, allocating a disk block before referencing it ensures that a system\ crash can't result in doubly-allocated blocks.\ \'a5 Existing consistency systems must be reimplemented for each file system\ \'a5 In Kudos, \f1\b change descriptors \f0\b0 represent all in-memory changes to the disk, and\ express these ordering requirements in a file system independent manner}

{\rtf1\mac\ansicpg10000\cocoartf824\cocoasubrtf330 {\fonttbl\f0\fswiss\fcharset77 Helvetica;\f1\fswiss\fcharset77 Helvetica-Oblique;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural
\f0\fs52 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0 \'a5 Give applications control over their change descriptors\ \'a5 Identifies a set of change descriptors generated by file system\ operations\ \'a5 Applications specify ordering requirements among changegroups\ \'a5 Example: Safely transform a file (at least one copy available no\ matter what)\ \'a5 Before: transform, then sync, then delete original \ \'a5 Changegroups: transform, \f1\i add dependency \f0\i0 , delete original\ \'a5 Result minimizes writes, should be faster}

{\rtf1\mac\ansicpg10000\cocoartf824\cocoasubrtf330 {\fonttbl\f0\fswiss\fcharset77 Helvetica;\f1\fswiss\fcharset77 Helvetica-Oblique;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\ql\qnatural\pardirnatural
\f0\fs52 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0 \'a5 Disks and applications\'d5 storage requirements are growing exponentially\ \'a5 Result: Increased application demands on file systems, both functionality\ (encryption, extensible metadata, snapshots...) and robustness (surviving failure:\
\f1\i consistency \f0\i0 )\ \'a5 Existing \'d2stackable\'d3 file system architectures simplify some feature development,\ but ignore consistency maintenance\ \'a5 File system interfaces limit application behavior: Robust applications must either\ fully synchronize (expensive) or use the raw disk (difficult)\ \
\f1\i The Kudos modular file system architecture makes file system features easy to develop, simplifies consistency maintenance, and supports new robust application semantics.}
